text.popuptext: International Commission on Stratigraphy ICS. Click Geol. TimeScale Foundation GSSP for boundary (GSSP) definitions, status and nomenclature.

CRETACEOUS = Thierry et al. (in Hardenbol et al., SEPM charts, 1998), with GTS2004 and Kilian Group (2004-2011) revisions; JURASSIC = Groupe Francais d'etude du Jurassique (1997); TRIASSIC = Mietto and Manfrin (in Hardenbol et al., SEPM charts, 1998), with GTS2004 and Kozur (2003 and pers. commun., 2006. 2010) and Marco Balini (2010) revisions; Permian = Low-Latitude suite from Kozur (2003), but see Permian suite (under Paleozoic ammonoids) by Henderson (2012).

CRETACEOUS = Thierry et al. (in Hardenbol et al., SEPM charts, 1998), with GTS2004 and Kilian Group (2004-2011) revisions; JURASSIC = Groupe Francais d'etude du Jurassique (1997); TRIASSIC = Mietto and Manfrin (in Hardenbol et al., SEPM charts, 1998), with GTS2004 and Kozur (2003 and pers. commun., 2006. 2010) and Marco Balini (2010) revisions; Permian = Low-Latitude suite from Kozur (2003), but see Permian suite (under Paleozoic ammonoids) by Henderson (2012).

TRIASSIC = Tethyan zones of Kozur'03 with Early Triassic modified after Orchard'07; PERMIAN-CARBONIFEROUS = GTS2012 diagrams of Henderson and of Davydov (zones used for Spline-fit of this age scale); DEVONIAN = Becker (GTS2012) suite used for spline-fit age model; SILURIAN = "Standard" of Mike Melchin in GTS2012; ORDOVICIAN = North Atlantic conodont zones (Figure 2.2 in Webby et al. (2004; The Great Ordovician Biodiversification Event); with ages (and some zones) modified by Roger Cooper (chart of Nov'2010 for GTS2012). Cooper's placement relative to Australia "Conop/spline-fit" zones is used here.); CAMBRIAN = South China zones by Chen et al (2010 pers. commun. to J.Ogg; during sessions at Nanjing Inst. Geol. Paleont.) as scaled by Peng and Babcock (GTS2012 graphics)

EARLY Anisian is traditionally the Aegean substage that begins in the Tethyan realm with the Japonites welteri Ammonoid zone. But, base of Conodont Ch. timorensis is used here for base of Anisian, hence of Aegean.

Late ( Age: 237.0 )

EARLY CARNIAN - BUT: "Cordevolian" is a controversial additional subdivision of Early Carnian that equates to D. canadensis and Trachyceras aon Ammonoid Zones. Bachmann (Aug2015 to J.Ogg): "As pointed out by KOZUR (2003), the priority subdivision of the Carnian into the Cordevolian, Julian and Tuvalian substages (MOJSOSIVICS et al. 1895) should be preserved. Lumping the original Cordevolian and Julian into a new extended Julian substage (e. g. KRYSTYN 1974) violates the priority without convincing faunistic reason. Very characteristic for the Cordevolian is the co-occurrence of Ladinian and Carnian elements in all fossil groups, whereas the Ladinian elements disappear around the base of the Julian. The high percentage of Ladinian elements, in addition to the first occurrence of many Carnian forms, is the reason why the Cordevolian was for a long time considered to represent the youngest substage of the Ladinian. The Julian begins with the Trachyceras aonoides Zone, which is characterised by both the disappearance of the last Ladinian holdovers and by the appearance of numerous new Carnian or Carnian-Norian types in all stratigraphically important fossil groups, especially well recognisable in radiolarian faunas. "

Yuan et al. / Lithos 204 (2014) 220?245 -- Supposing constant sedimentary rate between any two dated ash beds in view of the monotonous carbonate facies of the Changhsing Formation at the Meishan sections, the duration for the C. wangi Zone is from 254.14 Ma to 253.27 Ma (870 kyr), the C. subcarinata Zone is from 253.27 Ma to 253.12 Ma (150 kyr), the C. changxingensis Zone is from 253.12 Ma to 252.057 Ma (1063 kyr), the C. yini zone is from 252.057 Ma to 251.953 Ma (104 kyr), the C. meishanensis Zone is from 251.953 Ma to 251.932 Ma (21 kyr) [NOTE: there are 2 more brief conodont zones still to PT boundary at 251.90Ma] (Burgess et al., 2014; Shen et al., 2011). This is close to the astronomical calibration of the Meishan and Shangsi sections (Wu et al., 2013). BUT, used 254.15 (instead of 254.14) here to avoid having to explain the 0.1 change "after rounding" from GTS2012. which is really only 0.01 difference, well within the uncertainty!

Clarkina krystyni ( Age: 251.43 )

Basal age from Daxiakou is implied as 450 kyr above base of H. parvus from cyclostrat (Fig. B1 in Mingsong Li et al., 2015 in press). Genus "Neogondollela" is preferred by Orchard (May'07), and Neoclarkina is used in some Chinese sections. [Mike Orchard, Jan 2016 "I suggest using Neoclarkina krystyni (after Henderson), although the grounds for recognizing that genus are poor ? but not as poor as Clarkina!"] Kozur (2003) had used "Clarkina" carinata for this zone, but he wrote (2006. to Jim Ogg) that "Clarkina" krystyni is preferable for now. Note that all Perm/Tri boundary Neogondollela are now assigned as "Clarkina" by some boundary workers, e.g., Kozur 2003 (why?). Zone of Hindeodus planata used at Meishan -- shallower setting. "Carinata" zone eliminated by Sweet (1986), but used by Kozur (who also implied that FAD of carinata is perhaps one-third up in Oph. tibeticum ammonite zone (used here). Kozur (2003) had an overlying zone of Clarkina postcarinata, beginning at about 2/3rds up in Oph. tibeticum ammonite zone. However, he wrote (2006. to Jim Ogg) that this species is not described, therefore to not use this zone.

Stratigraphic range of Magniestheria mangaliensis (Jones), which evolved from M. rybinskensis (Novozhilov). Long span = Volpriehausen Formation above the Volpriehausen Sandstone. "Accompanying conodonts in the Werfen Group of Hungary (Pachycladina association) indicate Early Olenekian (late Smithian) age" (Kozur-Weems, 2010). Szurlies shows as just below base of CG6n => put as base of Cycle 3.3.

- ( Age: 248.8 )

Interval without conchostracans = base of Detfurth

Magniestheria deverta ( Age: 248.65 )

Lower Spathian of the Germanic Basin (uppermost Volpriehausen Formation, Detfurth Formation, lowermost Hardegsen Formation). Stratigraphic range of Magniestheria deverta (Novozhilov), in the middle and upper part of the zone together with Euestheria exsecta (Novozhilov) and Palaeolimnadia alsatica detfurthensis Kozur & Seidel. Szurlies (2007) shows as middle of CG7r => middle of Cycle 4.2.

Euestheria exsecta ( Age: 248.4 )

Co-occurrence of Euestheria exsecta (Novozhilov) and Palaeolimnadia ? nodosa(Novozhilov) without Magniestheria deverta (Novozhilov) and Euestheria albertii mahlerselli Kozur & Lepper n. subsp. Szurlies (2007) shows as base of Hardegsen Fm. "Euestheria exsecta clearly dominates in the E. exsecta Zone, but it is a rather long-ranging form that is very abundant also in the middle and upper part of the underlying M. deverta Zone and ranges up to the uppermost Spathian Hornestheria sollingensis Zone." (Kozur and Weems, 2010)

Euestheria albertii mahlerselli - Palaeolimnadia ? nodosa ( Age: 247.2 )

Co-occurrence of Euestheria albertii mahlerselli Kozur & Lepper n. subsp., E. exsecta (Novozhilov), Palaeolimnadia alsatica detfurthensis Kozur & Seidel and P. ? nodosa (Novozhilov). Szurlies (2007) shows as base of Solling Fm. "E. albertii mahlerselli species is rather long-ranging and occurs throughout the late Spathian and Aegean." (Kozur and Weems, 2010).

Hornestheria sollingensis ( Age: 247.0 )

Range of Hornestheria sollingensis Kozur & Lepper n. sp. Karlshafen Beds of the Solling Formation. Szurlies (2007)shows as uppermost CG10n => base of s6.3.

Euestheria albertii mahlerselli ? P. alsatica alsatica ( Age: 246.8 )

Base of Aegaen (Fig. 16 in Kozur-Weems'10). Co-occurrence of Euestheria albertii mahlerselli Kozur & Lepper n. subsp. and Palaeolimnadia alsatica alsatica (Reible). "E. albertii mahlerselli species is rather longranging and occurs throughout the late Spathian and Aegean." (Kozur and Weems, 2010)

Euestheria albertii albertii ( Age: 245.77 )

Base of L. caurus ammonite zone. Occurrence of Euestheria albertii albertii (Voltz) without Diaplexa tigjanensis Novozhilov.. Base of Bithynian (Fig. 16 in Kozur-Weems'10)

Diaplexa tigjanensis ( Age: 245.09 )

DASH -- base of N. osmani ammonite zone. Occurrence of Diaplexa tigjanensis Novozhilov without Xiangxiella bicostata Shen.. Base of Pelsonian (Fig. 16 in Kozur-Weems'10)

Xiangxiella bicostata ( Age: 243.43 )

DASHED -- base of P. trinodosus. Range of Xiangxiella bicostata Shen. ca. 40% up in Illyrian (Fig. 16 in Kozur-Weems'10)

Euestheria franconica ( Age: 241.5 )

DOTTED --- Range of Euestheria franconica (Reible). Base of Fassanian (Fig. 16 in Kozur-Weems'10). "As this zone occurs only in brackish beds, it is possible that it overlaps with the Xiangxiella bicostata Zone and that Xiangxiella bicostata does not occur for facies reasons. However, it is also possible that the X. bicostata Zone is restricted to the upper Anisian." (Kozur and Weems, 2010).

Euestheria minuta ( Age: 239.1 )

DOTTED -- Range of Euestheria minuta (von Zieten) without Xiangxiella and Laxitextella multireticulata (Reible). Base of Longobardian (Fig. 16 in Kozur-Weems'10). "The Euestheria minuta Zone is the youngest Triassic conchostracan Zone that occurs not only in the entire northern hemisphere, but also in parts of Gondawana (North Africa and Argentina). Despite this fact, it is not characterized by a very distinctive fauna, but rather by the absence of any distinctive taxa, such as Diaplexa, Vileginia, and Xiangxiella, which occur below E. minuta, and Laxitextella, which occurs above the E. minuta Zone. In most of these faunas, only E. minuta is present." (Kozur and Weems, 2010)

Laxitextella multireticulata ( Age: 237.0 )

DASHED -- diagrammed as Base of D. canadensis ammonite zone. Occurrence of Laxitextella multireticulata (Reible) without L. laxitexta (Sandberger). "Early Cordevolian. In the Germanic Basin, the FAD of L. multireticulata coincides with the FAD of the palynotaxon Patinasporites densus Leschik. Slightly higher is the FAD of Vallasporites ignacii Leschik. In the Carnian GSSP at Stuores Wiesen, these two species begin immediately above the base of the Carnian, as defined by the base of the Daxatina canadiensis Zone (Broglio Loriga et al. 1999)." (Kozur-Weems'10)

Gregoriusella fimbriata - Laxitexella laxitexta ( Age: 236.53 )

DASHED --Diagrammed as 75% up in D. canadensis ammonite zone. Occurrence of Gregoriusella fimbriata (Warth) and Laxitexella laxitexta (Sandberger). Upper half of Cordevolian (as used by Kozur)

TOP ( Age: 235.3 )

DOTTED -- Base of Julian (placed here as 50% up in merged Julian-Cordovalian). "The upper boundary of this zone is difficult to define, because in the Germanic Basin it is followed by an interval barren of conchostracans that is particularly rich in pedogenic soil beds. A stratigraphic gap then occurs." (Kozur-Weems'10)

[ Schilfsandstein fauna ] ( Age: 234.37 )

Base of Schifsandstein. "Gregoriusella cf. G. fimbriata and Laxitextella cf. L. laxitexta are present in the basal Schilfsandstein, but this fauna is poorly preserved. The lower Schilfsandstein above the basal beds is again dominated by Laxitextella of the L. laxitexta group, but Gregoriusella cf. G. fimbriata is no longer present or else very rare. A further change occurs in the upper Schilfsandstein, where in the Gaildorf Horizon a fauna occurs that contains many Laxitextella of the L. laxitexta group, among them a new species. Palaeolimnadia n. sp. is also common. This new species may be identical with Palaeolimnadia n. sp. from the lower Bluewater Creek Formation of northeastern Arizona." (Kozur and Weems, 2010)

Base of Tuvalian, immediately above the middle Carnian wet intermezzo. Range Zone of Eosolimnadiopsis gallegoi Kozur. Earliest Tuvalian, immediately above the middle Carnian wet intermezzo (MCWI) sensu Kozur & Bachmann (2008a).

DASHED -- Base of P. planorbis. ca. 15% up in Hettangian ("Early, but not earliest Hettangian"). Co-occurrence of Bulbilimnadia sheni Kozur & Weems and other Liassic conchostracans along with dominant Euestheria brodieana (Jones). B. sheni is more common than B. killianorum within the genus Bulbilimnadia, and by the upper B. sheni Zone is the only Bulbilimnadia species present.
